 (file)\r\nsave(ok): /tmp/brkrun (dataset)\r\naction summary:\r\n  add (ok: 1)\r\n  save (ok: 1)\r\n(datalad3-dev) mih@meiner /tmp/brkrun (git)-[master] % datalad run git rm some\r\n[INFO   ] == Command start (output follows) ===== \r\nrm 'some'\r\n[INFO   ] == Command exit (modification check follows) ===== \r\nFailed to run ['git', '-c', 'receive.autogc=0', '-c', 'gc.auto=0', 'add', '--verbose', '--', 'some'] under '/tmp/brkrun'. Exit code=128. out= err=fatal: pathspec 'some' did not match any files\r\nfatal: pathspec 'some' did not match any files\r\n```\r\n\r\ninside `run` calls `add('.')`, which seems like the right thing to do -- although maybe it should be `save('.')`, going back to #2043 and #2428.\r\n\r\nApplying this diff\r\n\r\n```diff\r\n--- a/datalad/interface/run.py\r\n+++ b/datalad/interface/run.py\r\n@@ -223,5 +223,5 @@ def run_command(cmd, dataset=None, message=None, rerun_info=None):\r\n                  msg_path)\r\n         raise exc\r\n     else:\r\n-        for r in ds.add('.', recursive=True, message=msg):\r\n+        for r in ds.save(path='.', recursive=True, message=msg):\r\n             yield r\r\n```\r\n\r\nsolves the issue at hand (see example above), but breaks pretty much any existing `run` tests we have.", "closed_by": {"login": "mih", "id": 136479, "node_id": "MDQ6VXNlcjEzNjQ3OQ==", "avatar_url": "https://avatars.githubusercontent.com/u/136479?v=4", "gravatar_id": "", "url": "https://api.github.com/users/mih", "html_url": "https://github.com/mih", "followers_url": "https://api.github.com/users/mih/followers", "following_url": "https://api.github.com/users/mih/following{/other_user}", "gists_url": "https://api.github.com/users/mih/gists{/gist_id}", "starred_url": "https://api.github.com/users/mih/starred{/owner}{/repo}", "subscriptions_url": "https://api.github.com/users/mih/subscriptions", "organizations_url": "https://api.github.com/users/mih/orgs", "repos_url": "https://api.github.com/users/mih/repos", "events_url": "https://api.git